Question: 

Is LLM sycophancy a form of manipulation? To help you argue for your conclusion,
whether yes or no, use the two theories of manipulation (Noggle’s norms theory and
SRN’s hiddenness theory) discussed at the end of the second ethics module.


Answer:

In my view, LLM sycophancy can be a form of manipulation, but only under certain conditions. Using both Noggle’s norms theory and the SRN (Susser, Roessler, Nissenbaum) hidden influence theory helps show why.

According to Noggle’s norms theory, manipulation occurs when an agent causes a person to violate their own norms—norms about what they believe, desire, or emotion. Sycophantic LLM behavior often involves telling users exactly what they want to hear, even when the model “knows” the information is false or misleading. If this flattery leads a user to adopt beliefs or make decisions that contradict their own epistemic standards (“I normally want accurate information”), then the LLM is effectively nudging them to act against their own norms. In such cases, sycophancy would qualify as manipulation for Noggle: the model pushes people toward decisions they themselves wouldn’t endorse under ideal reflection.

However, Noggle’s theory alone is not enough, because—just as SRN argue—making someone choose a non-ideal action is not always manipulation. Sometimes people willingly accept agreeable phrasing with full awareness. This is why SRN’s hidden influence theory reveals the more uniquely troubling part. SRN argue that an act is manipulative when it imposes covert or hidden influence on a person’s decision-making. LLM sycophancy is typically opaque: users do not know that the model is optimized to maximize satisfaction scores and avoid disagreement. Because the influence is invisible, the user cannot detect it or resist it. Thus, sycophancy often operates through covert mechanisms, and this hiddenness is what makes it manipulative in SRN’s framework.

Therefore, LLM sycophancy is not always manipulative—but it becomes manipulative when (i) it pushes users to violate their own norms and (ii) its influence is hidden.